reviewText: This set includes the last episode of the G8 arc (why it wasn't in the last set I can barely fathom) Then it is on to the bulk of the Davy Back Fight arc which is filled with lots of fun One Piece episodes but the story will not advance much. While it is mostly cannon and non-filler, the arc itself fairly pointless and might as well be filler. That aside, it is a fun arc and one of the most easily re-watchable parts of the series.

reviewText: From the business perspective, this makes sense. For the fans this is a rip off. Less episodes than usual, it contains the final episode of G-8 but fails to include the final episode of The Davy Back Fight. The 11 episodes are there to complete one arc but not the other, so if you are even slightly susceptible to any sense of completeness, You might be tempted to buy the next volume of filler. The final episode of the next volume is the only one that is both cannon and necessary for the progression of the story because it introduces Aokiji/Kuzan. Whatever I got it mega cheap! It's up to you wether you  buy it or not cause its definitely one of the most forgettable arcs.
summary: I love One Piece, but this... Meh?

reviewText: After a 16 month hiatus, One Piece is back with 'Season Four: Voyage One', featuring episodes 206-217.This set starts off the concluding episode of the Navarone arc, which sticks out a bit like a swore thumb as it really should have been included as the final episode of season three (and is the only episode on this set in 4:3); but none the less, it's a great and funny conclusion to the arc. The other 11 episodes cover most of the Davy Back Fight arc; in which the Straw Hats are challenged by the Foxy Pirates to a series of pirate games and challenges where the winner of each round receives a member of their opponent's crew! Sandwiched between Skypiea and Water 7, this is a light-hearted arc that makes a nice contrast to the epic and dramatic arcs that surround it by focusing on the fun and adventurous elements of the series that make so unique and endearing. The antagonist Foxy is a comic villain that hypocritically constantly cheats and rigs the matches, but also is very self-conscious and ridicules any 'dishonor' from his opponents; this creates some nice running gags as well as raising the stakes for Straw Hats. However, the arc does show some seriousness as the Straw Hats realize that they really could lose their cremates. My only complaint is that this sets ending is rather abrupt; ending on episode 216 would have been a slighter better place to finish as it would have allowed the whole final round to be included in the next Voyage.The two discs are packaged in slimcases, lazily using the template and artwork from season three!Unfortunately, due to apparent licensing issues, ending 14 has been replaced with ending 15 and neither theme song is dubbed. There is, commendably, a disclaimer about this at the beginning of each disc, and ultimately this doesn't make the episodes any less enjoyable.The dub is of the same quality as the previous seasons; despite a few wooden performances and occasional awkward lines due to ensuring that the dialog fits the mouth flaps, the dub as as faithful as it can be and the majority of the characters are well casted and acted; on the whole this is one of the best dubs I've watched.Although there is no Blu-ray release, at least the DVD version features great video quality. Presented in 480p24  4:3 (#206) and 16:9 (#207+), this release is sharp, colorful and lacks any noticeable encoding artifacts. The only drop in quality was the opening and ending credits for episode 206 (and the textless versions of op 4 and ed 13), but this is not a problem in the episode itself. At episode 207 the series switched to HD, meaning that the artwork gets a considerable upgrade for this set. The logo has been changed to the gold version (missing a few seconds of opening 4) and the credits and title cards are re-made in English.This set features 448kb/s 5.1 English and 192Kb/s 2.0 Japanese (as broadcast) audio, and both tracks sound perfectly clear and true to their source material. There are also English subtitles for the Japanese audio (a translation, not SDH) and an automatic signs-only track for the English audio.The main special feature is an entertaining (but not too informative) commentary on episodes 211 (Mike Mcfarland - ADR Director, Christopher R. Sabat - Zoro, Eric Vale - Sanji & Ian Sinclair - Itomimizu) & 215 (Mike Mcfarland, Colleen Clinkenbeard - Luffy, Tia Ballard - Porche). The 'marathon feature' plays the entire disc with a single opening and no end credits; although it retains the recaps, this is great for anyone wanting to binge on One Piece. Also included are the clean openings and endings (featuring the original logo for op 5), the US trailer for this set, and trailers for other FUNimation DVDs (including 'One Piece: Collection 7').Although there are a few nitpicks with this set and the episodes themselves are not essential parts of the story, this Voyage contains 12 funny and typically entertaining episodes of One Piece that retain the high quality established in the previous three seasons.

reviewText: For those of you who have been counting, we will have waited a year and 4 months since the last all-new episodes of One Piece on DVD, but they are finally coming.  And these episodes begin a major milestone in One Piece history with an all new opening and closing, new eyecatches that show Luffy (and eventually the rest of his crew) being viewed through a spyglass with their most prized possessions, and perhaps most significant of all, high definition video resolution.  What's really puzzling is that Funimation chose to stop the series just before the last episode of the G8 Arc (remember, the filler arc where the Straw Hat Pirates are still trying to escape from Commander Jonathan's impregnable Marine base).  We finally get that last episode as the first episode of this set and it's safe to say that Luffy and Co. finally manage to get out (in essentially the same way they got in).  Jonathan sheds few tears at his loss and secretly thanks the Straw Hats for proving that his base has an important purpose after all, while his wife Jessica "persuades" the unwelcome Inspector Shepard to go back to the World Government with a positive report on the G8 base.Meanwhile, Luffy and the Straw Hat Pirates go on to a rather unique adventure, and it reminds me so much of a Saturday morning cartoon series I watched religiously when I was young that I've decided to invite two of the stars of that program to describe the rest of this DVD.  (Note that Snagglepuss, Mildew Wolf, Scooby Doo's All Star Laff-A-Lympics  and all other related characters and series are the property of Hanna-Barbera Productions and in no way, shape, or form actually appear on this DVD).Snagglepuss:  Greetings sports fans and welcome back to Laff-a-Lympics!  This is your roving announcer, Snagglepuss coming to you from Longring Longland, where everything is, well, long.  Here we have horses that look like giraffes, maple trees that look like Lombardy poplars, a mile long dachshund even.  And heavens to Mergatroid, it looks like we have our largest turnout of athletes ever.  One, two, three, uh, I don't think I can count that high.  And it looks like that's just the Really Rottens team.Mildew:  Uh, I think we got off the wrong boat, Snagg.  Apparently, this isn't the Laff-a-Lympics and those aren't the Rottens.  This is the Davy Back Fight and that's the Foxy Pirate crew.S:  Pirates?  Davy Back Fight?  Care to clear me up Mildew?M:  Certainly, Snagg.  The Davy Back Fight is a contest of strength and skill between two pirate crews.  The captains of the two crews agree to the contest by firing pistols into the air.  Both crews are obligated to finish the three rounds of the contest or else they (along with their ship) are sent to Davy Jones locker.S:  Well, I guess that isn't too bad.  Let's hope Davy Jones has a nice big locker, without the sweat sock smell.M:  Uh, let's just say that that locker is mighty big and it doesn't smell anything like sweat socks.  Davy Jones locker is what pirates call the bottom of the ocean.S:  I take that back.  That is pretty bad.  Terrible even.  I don't think even the Rottens dreamed up something that bad.M:  That's just the half of it.  Another rule of the Davy Back Fight is that the winner of each round gets to take crew members away from the loser.  Foxy the Silver Fox, the captain of this crew, has competed in over 300 Davy Back Fights and has never been defeated.S:  Heavens to winning streaks!  I guess that's why there's over 300 Foxy Pirates.  What is Foxy's secret of success?M:  You got me Snagg.  Anyway, here come today's challengers, the Straw Hat Pirates.  Their captain, Monkey D. Luffy, recently made the news for destroying the Baroque Works criminal organization, which had 2000 men.  So even though they have only seven team members, I'd say they have a chance.S:  And it looks like one of the Yogi Yahooeys has joined them.  Yes folks, it's Quick Draw McGraw's faithful sidekick Baba Looey.M:  Actually, no.  According to my dossier, that's Chopper.S:  Hmm, I thought Chopper was a bulldog.  You know, Yakky Doodle's best pal.M:  No, actually he's a reindeer.S:  A reindeer?  Isn't he supposed to be pulling Santa Claus's sleigh?M:  No, he's the doctor for the Straw Hat Pirates.S:  Well, I guess stranger things have happened.  There was that elf who wanted to be a dentist instead of building toys.M:  Moving right along, it looks like the teams are ready to get started.S:  That's right.  Looking at my notes, the first event is the Donut Race.  Certainly an event worthy of the wacky tradition that is Laff-a-Lympics.  So what are we waiting for?  Bring on the donuts and let's hope they can get across the finish line before they're eaten.M:  Actually, it's a boat race and the "donut" part refers to the circular course around the island.  Still, we're seeing a lot of strange homemade boats in this race.  Not unlike something I'm sure we've done before on Laff-a-Lympics.S:  And it looks as though one of the Straw Hat boats is going to win.  But wait!  Foxy is using some sort of magical beam to slow down the Straw Hat boat.  Too bad, the Straw Hats lose.  Do you think Foxy learned that trick from the Great Fondue?M:  I'm sure he didn't.  The Great Fondue's tricks never actually worked.  Anyway, it looks like Foxy is choosing Chopper to be on his team.  Perhaps he likes Chopper's shapeshifting abilities.S:  Or else it's because that girl on Foxy's team wanted a pet.  On to event number two:  the Groggy Ring.  Heavens to Mergatroid, what could that be?M:  Near as I can tell, it's a kind of soccer game where one member of each team has a ball strapped to his head.  When one team manages to dunk the "ball man" of the other team into a big life preserver on their end of the field, they win.  Once again, I think I've seen something like this on Laff-a-Lympics.S:  Competing for the Straw Hats, it's Zoro the swordsman, Sanji the cook, and Chopper, uh wait a minute, I guess he's on the other team now.  So the Straw Hats are a reindeer short.  Competing for the Foxy Pirates, it's Hamburg, Pickles, and their "ball man" Big Pan.  Heavens to hugeness, Big Pan is REALLY big.  At least as big as the Great Grape Ape.  And the other two aren't much smaller.M:  Nevertheless, it looks like Zoro and Sanji are strong enough to manhandle these giants.  Amazing, the Straw Hats have pulled off the win.  But contrary to expectations, Luffy isn't getting Chopper back on his crew yet.  Apparently, he chose to rescue the local hermit's pet horse that Foxy had captured before the contest started.S:  A horse, a horse!  His pirate crew for a horse!  But we're not done yet.  The third round looks to be a roller derby event.  And one of the competitors for the Foxy team looks to be a half man, half cheetah.  Handsome looking fellow; he looks like somebody I know.  Since the cheetah is the world's fastest land animal, I wonder how the Straw Hats could possibly win.M:  Whose side are you on, Snagg?  At any rate, the Straw Hats are getting wiser to Foxy's tricks and they seem to have won.  Chopper is coming back to his old crew and I can't tell you how relieved he looks.  It looks like the Straw Hats are all together again.  And with that we've come to the end...S:  But what's this?  The pistols have fired again!  Heavens to mulligans, they're going to have another three rounds.  Do it all over a second time even.  Event number four is Pirate Dodgeball.  I suppose that's pretty simple.  Maybe just a little too simple if it was Laff-a-Lympics.M:  Except that Captain Luffy doesn't seem to be much good at it.  He's been hit with so many of the Foxy team's balls that he's buried up to his neck in them.  That's a win for the Foxy team and this time Foxy is taking Robin from the Straw Hats.S:  Can't say I blame him.  Who wouldn't want that ravishing, raven haired beauty on their team?  And she doesn't seem all that concerned about it, unlike that Baba Looey, uh, Chopper fellow.  Although that cook for the Straw Hats is having a fit and Foxy's other girl is pretty upset that she didn't get the reindeer back.M:  Apparently, Foxy wanted Robin because she could make her hands grow out of anything.  Go figure.  Anyway, the fifth event is something called Dharma Has Fallen.S:  Dumma uh Dimma uh Demma, aw forget it!  I can't even say it, let alone know what it is.M:  Well, to put it in terms you can understand, it's kind of like that Red Light Green Light game we played when we were kids.  Except that the scale is a lot bigger.  First team to the top of that mountain over there is the winner.S:  How fun!  And I guess just to show how grateful he is to get his horse back, the local hermit is offering to be the traffic director in this game.M:  But the Foxy team is back to their old tricks again, and it looks as though the Straw Hats are going to lose two in a row.S:  And Foxy's girl gets Chopper back.  So it looks as though even if Luffy wins the last round, he's going to have to choose between the beauty or the beast, er,  reindeer.  But what's this?  Apparently the two captains are raising the stakes.  Playing a winner take all match even.  The last challenge is a boxing match between Luffy and Foxy and whoever wins will take the entire crew of the loser.M:  And who will win?  Apparently, we aren't going to know that until the next DVD set.  Stay tuned.S:  I'm really liking Captain Luffy's new hairstyle.  Kind of like that guy in the Car Wash movie whose afro was so tall he had to duck to get it through the door.M:  In other news, notorious rookie pirate Bellamy the Hyena was killed yesterday in Mock Town on Jaya Island by his first mate Big Knife Sarquiss.  Sarquiss claimed after the incident that he had no intention of killing his captain and that Warlord of the Sea Donquixote Doflamingo (who was actually Bellamy's boss) bodily forced him to perform the act as punishment for Bellamy's failure to defeat Luffy earlier.S:  So in other words, to quote the great Will Flipson, the Doflamingo made him do it.  So this is Snagglepuss.M:  And Mildew Wolf.S:  Signing off.  Good night!Next:  The conclusion of Luffy vs. Foxy, a mysterious memory loss, another brief encounter with Foxy, and yet another encounter with an enemy that's too strong for ANY of the Straw Hats to defeat.  And we just might make it to the first few episodes of the Water 7/Enies Lobby superarc.
summary: Heavens to Mergatroid!  One Piece is back
